Class JmsEventTransportImpl

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.betfair.cougar.core.api.transports.AbstractRegisterableTransport

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    com.betfair.cougar.core.api.BindingDescriptorRegistrationListener, com.betfair.cougar.core.api.transports.EventTransport, org.springframework.beans.factory.Aware, org.springframework.beans.factory.InitializingBean, org.springframework.context.ApplicationContextAware

    public class JmsEventTransportImpl
extends com.betfair.cougar.core.api.transports.AbstractRegisterableTransport
implements com.betfair.cougar.core.api.transports.EventTransport, org.springframework.context.ApplicationContextAware, org.springframework.beans.factory.InitializingBean
    This class implements an abstract JMS based transport implementation. The implementation contains a set of defaults for a JMS transport that are overrideable through spring config if you'd like to do something different. This class must be sub-classed to create a concrete impl.

      • publish

        public void publish(com.betfair.cougar.core.api.events.Event event)
             throws com.betfair.cougar.core.api.exception.CougarException
        Publish the supplied event to the destination. The destination address (to publish the event to) will be derived using the plugged destination resolver. If you want to implement different / more advanced destination resolution, implement your own JMSDestinationResolver. Note that obviously both the publisher and consumer must arrive at the same destination name, so should be using the same convention (since they're unlikely to be running in the same Cougar instance) The event will be published using a thread from the pool and its associated jms session

      • subscribe

        public void subscribe(String eventName,
             Object[] args,
             com.betfair.cougar.core.api.ev.ExecutionObserver observer)
        Subscribe to events of the supplied name. Your passed in observer will be called back in each of the following circumstances:
        • onResult for each message
        • onSubscription will be called when a connection is successfully established to the message broker, supplying you a Subscription object, which can use to close your connection
        • onException if an exception occurs when establishing the connection.
        • if the related SubscriptionEventListener (if supported by this JMS impl) detects loss or failure of connection to the broker.
        The destination address (to listen for events from) will be derived using the plugged destination resolver. If you want to implement different / more advanced destination resolution, implement your own JMSDestinationResolver. Note that both the publisher and consumer must arrive at the same destination name, so should be using the same convention (since they're unlikely to be running in the same Cougar instance)
        Specified by:
        subscribe in interface com.betfair.cougar.core.api.transports.EventTransport
        Parameters:
        eventName - - the name of the event, matching the event name defined in the IDD
        args - - subscription arguments, note that if you've asked for a durable subscription, then you MUST supply a durable subscription identifier as the zeroth argument
        observer - - the callback to be notified on message events

      • setExecutionContext

        public void setExecutionContext(com.betfair.cougar.api.ExecutionContext executionContext)
        Sets the execution context associated with this SETI instance. Note that there must be one of these things - and that this class will create a default one for you. If you don't need anything special, this is almost certainly fine for you. Note that if you're setting this property and you want to use multiple event transports, you MUST set something in the identity chain to differentiate one instance from another, otherwise you won't be able to tell which transport is which when your app is called back and you start it up.
